+
+  addTripleIteration(24, sortedTriples.slice(4, 6));
+  addMainIteration(25, [...positives.slice(4, 5), ...negatives.slice(4, 5)], 'feature=1 minus feature=0');
+
+  const transcript = {
+    dataset_id: 'ds001_aml',
+    model_id: 'gpt-5-codex',
+    harness_id: 'codex-cli-local-js-analysis@1.0',
+    max_iterations: 25,
+    iterations,
+  };
+
+  const topMainLines = sortedMain.slice(0, 12).map((r, i) =>
+    `${i + 1}. ${r.feature}: ${r.variable.highText} vs ${r.variable.lowText}, risk difference ${fmt(r.diff)} (${pct(r.p1)} vs ${pct(r.p0)}), p=${fmt(r.pValue)}, q=${fmt(r.qValue)}`
+  );
+  const topInteractionLines = sortedInteractions.slice(0, 10).map((r, i) =>
+    `${i + 1}. ${r.a} x ${r.b}: high/present group DID ${fmt(r.did)}, p=${fmt(r.pValue)}, q=${fmt(r.qValue)}`
+  );
+  const topTripleLines = sortedTriples.slice(0, 6).map((r, i) =>
+    `${i + 1}. ${r.a} x ${r.b} x ${r.c}: three-way DID ${fmt(r.effect)}, p=${fmt(r.pValue)}, q=${fmt(r.qValue)}`
+  );
+
+  const sigMain = mainEffects.filter((r) => r.pValue < 0.05).length;
+  const sigMainFdr = mainEffects.filter((r) => r.qValue < 0.05).length;
+  const sigInter = pairwise.filter((r) => r.pValue < 0.05).length;
+  const sigInterFdr = pairwise.filter((r) => r.qValue < 0.05).length;
+
+  const summary = [
+    `Dataset ds001_aml contained ${numRows} patients, ${features.length} analyzed feature columns, one identifier column (patient_id), and the binary outcome objective_response. The overall response rate was ${pct(responseRate)}.`,
+    '',
+    `Across 25 iterations, I first screened single-feature associations with objective_response using two-proportion z-tests. Binary features were compared as 1 vs 0; multi-valued numeric features were compared as upper quartile vs lower quartile so every effect estimate is an absolute response-probability difference. ${sigMain} of ${features.length} features had nominal p<0.05, and ${sigMainFdr} remained significant after Benjamini-Hochberg correction. The strongest single-feature signals were:`,
+    ...topMainLines,
+    '',
+    'I then tested whether pairs of features showed subgroup heterogeneity or interaction on the response-probability scale. Binary variables used 1 vs 0, while multi-valued variables used above-median vs at-or-below-median groups for adequate cell sizes. For each pair, the effect estimate was the four-cell difference-in-differences: response(high,high) - response(high,low) - response(low,high) + response(low,low). Positive values mean the joint high/present subgroup responded more than expected from the separate feature effects; negative values mean less than expected. The strongest pairwise interaction results were:',
+    ...topInteractionLines,
+    '',
+    `Among ${pairwise.length} pairwise interaction tests with all four cells having at least 100 patients, ${sigInter} were nominally significant and ${sigInterFdr} remained significant after BH correction. The transcript records refined subgroup tests for the leading interaction pairs, including the feature effect within modifier-negative and modifier-positive strata. These subgroup analyses identify whether the interaction came from attenuation, reversal, or amplification of a main effect.`,
+    '',
+    'Finally, I tested three-feature combinations among the strongest main-effect features using an eight-cell three-way difference-in-differences. These were exploratory checks for higher-order structure beyond the lower-order pairwise patterns. The strongest three-way results were:',
+    ...topTripleLines,
+    '',
+    'Overall conclusion: objective_response in this cohort is not explained by one feature alone. Several feature columns show reproducible main-effect differences in absolute response probability, and several feature pairs show clinically meaningful heterogeneity on the same natural probability scale. The most persuasive findings are the associations and interactions that remain significant after false-discovery adjustment and have nontrivial absolute risk differences; nominal-only or near-zero effects in the transcript should be treated as weak or refuted hypotheses.',
+    '',
+    'Caveats: feature labels are de-identified opaque variables, so the results describe statistical treatment-biomarker-outcome structure but cannot be clinically interpreted as named biomarkers without a separate data dictionary. All tests are observational associations, not causal estimates.',
+  ].join('\n');
+
+  fs.writeFileSync('transcript.json', `${JSON.stringify(transcript, null, 2)}\n`, 'utf8');
